segments.text: OK. My name is Richard Brown, and I'm senior vice president of planning for the Woodlands Corporation.
It's almost 1991, and I've spent the last 16 years here full time overseeing the real estate portfolio of Mitchell from the planning strategy and implementation
phase, most of that time being spent on the new town called the Woodlands.

I came here with a career that included 25 years of running my own consulting professional firm of planners, engineers, and architects, which had, when I left, five offices, New York, New Jersey, Maryland, Atlanta, Georgia, Baton Rouge, Louisiana.
And we specialized in
a broad spectrum of professional services, but my real love was new community planning and development.
I started my career in the early 50s as a professional engineer, broadening into urban planning and architecture, and became a consultant to many
communities, both for their planning boards and governing bodies, as well as servicing the real estate development industry in a wide variety of projects from industrial development.
How did you get into the new community concept or framework of things?
I was retained by the Rouse Company to do the planning and engineering on a regional shopping mall in Willowbrook, New Jersey, called Willowbrook in Wayne, New Jersey.

And in the process of that project, they announced to me that they had bought 11,000 acres in Maryland between Baltimore and Washington to do a new city, and wondered if I would come down and take a look at what they thought they wanted to do, since up to that point, they were regional moral developers.
But Jim Rouse had an idea that suburban sprawl communities were not the best way to develop this nation.
new communities were.
And I went down there in 1965.
Excuse me, how would you define a new community from that framework then or now, if there's any difference?
Well, I think up until then and still prevailing today, the development industry are really geared up to be what I call shelter builders.
They build houses, and your Sunday real estate section is full of houses.
And they sell living rooms and ceiling fans and back decks.
And the thrust really is the shelter they're selling.
There's very few people who are community builders.
A community builder not only provides a shelter, but he takes on the responsibility of providing a high quality of life for those residents to encompass all opportunities that are possible.
to create an environment where people can live good lives and cover a broad cross-section of housing.
Most subdivisions and developments are pretty monolithic in their price structure.
New community attempts to have housing for the very poor, the very rich, and everybody in between in accordance with some economic demographic profile so that you have the vibrant mixture of people.
And that's what new communities do.
try to provide the retail and employment components of life also in the project.
And that's part of the inception of the whole community plan?
The conception of the plan is that you shouldn't have to spend one or two hours a day out of your life commuting to and from work.
It would be great if you could get there in two to three minutes, which is the way I've lived for the last 30 years.
Because I've lived in new towns since the early 60s.
And I guess I've lost touch with what the real world is like.
It's all right.
That's all right.
All right.
So you were developing, you had become affiliated, I guess, with the new community town concept.
Yeah, the Rouse Company asked me to come down, and after a few days of discussions, I was put in charge of,
taking the conceptual plans and doing the hard line planning, the engineering, the county approvals that were necessary, take the bids, get the development built for the opening.
So I was headed for that.
That was a tremendous career.
Yeah, it was a wonderful experience.
How old were you then, roughly?
I was in my, I guess, early 40s or late 30s.
It was a wonderful experience to start with a clean slate and say, you know, where do the roads go?
Where should the neighborhoods be?
What is the fabric of community?
What kind of an infrastructure should you have from the physical side as well as the social side?
Can we take the experiences we've had and weave together a community that serves its people?
I could mention that for a number of years I was mayor of a town in New Jersey undergoing very rapid growth.
We're getting 3,000 building permits a year.
And I knew all the problems of trying to provide libraries and recreation and public works expansions and services for a growing population.
That was a great piece of experience.
I think that was incredible.
It really was.
I bet very few architects have had that side.
That's correct.
So that was an in-depth.
training session to help prepare me for new community development work, which is really what I love to do.
And then how did the Texas Connection develop?
After we got Columbia, Maryland open, the Routes Company had wanted me to stay on, but I had my own company, as I mentioned.
I had taken a sabbatical for a year and a half to get Columbia open, so I said no.
We expanded our activity in the new community field, and I think we did six or seven of the 12 or 13 HUD community projects.
Flower Man was one.
St. Charles was another.
Ganonda was a third.
We did Peachtree City, but at the last minute, they decided to stay private.
And of course, we did that.
That was in Georgia.
That was in Atlanta.
Yeah, southwest of Atlanta.
That's still doing very nicely now.
But the other HUD communities didn't make it, basically.
No, they didn't make it for predetermined reasons.
They had weak, inexperienced sponsors, not enough staying power financially.
They were in poor locations where the markets were not strong.
To build it in town, you need a great location.
You need to be on Interstate Highway, which the Williams did.
You need to be near a major airport, which it is.
You need to be near an urban center that's expanding and has dynamic...

vitality which houston does and so all the things will work you need a patient strong sponsor that can stand the deep investments that it takes the first 10 years before you turn profitable a few people are committed to do that yeah they're all looking for a quick return every quarter yeah the bank wants you to borrow the money and return it that same year it takes a long time to develop
these projects, it's nothing to think in terms of 20, 30, 40 years.
But anyway, George Mitchell came to Columbia, Maryland, and visited me at my office there.
I was pretty well known.
I guess that was in 68, 69.
and invited me down here to take a look at this property.
I wonder who led him to you.
Do you know, or other than just your reputation?
No, I think it was the Columbia.
Columbia had the reputation.

It was the first new town on the East Coast, and when they came and found out that I had my role in it, and that I was a consulting firm with an office right there in the American City building in downtown Columbia, it was logical to continue.
on and was a good source of potential clients and so forth.
So George then retained my firm to come down and help.
What did you think about his idea, that initial conversation?
Do you remember any aspect of that?
Yeah, I remember him asking me what it took to do a new town, and I told him it took a whole host of disciplines, engineers, planners, architects, economists, market people.
and a commitment for long-term investment and so forth.
And he said, OK. And I'm prepared to do all that.
And so I became a consultant to the project.
And just like with the Routes Company, when that was done, he said, well, why don't you stay on?
And again, I said no and went away to do Peachtree City for Pipps Land Company, which I did for a year.
including some work in Florida.
But I kept getting phone calls.
Why don't you come back?
Why don't you come back?
So when there was a break in major projects, I agreed to come back for a month and take a look.
And at the end of that 30 days, I decided to stay.
Oh, was that right?
This was in the fall of 1974.
But now, you had been here earlier than in 72?
Well, I was here in 70, 71, 72 when we did the planning.
Then I went away for two years.
Is this basic structure your conception, pretty much, the layout of the villages?
Well, let me say, to be totally fair, there was a team of people involved.
Robert Gladstone did the market studies
economic reports which have a strong bearing on what you build because there's a market there to buy it.
We had McCard here from the University of Pennsylvania who was an environmentalist who hammered home
the preservation of the forest concept and the forest preserves, which really is our signature.
And we still respect a lot of what he said, some of which we had to change.
Nevertheless, he had a very positive influence.
And then William Pereira, an architect on the West Coast.
George used to say, well, we've got the best from the West Coast and the best from the East Coast.
And Richard Brown, associate, and he
William Carrera got together, and we had numerous workshops over the year doing concept planning, master planning.
And we tried a lot of things.
We tried linear plans.
We tried historic gridiron patterns.
And in the end, I think the Columbia model
proved to be the most viable, which was a series of residential villages and a very strong employment corridor along I-45.
Your initial plan, what was the acreage?
Was it 7,000?
It's 25 now.
But it was 17 at that time.
When I came back full time, one of the first things I did was lobby, pick up that next 8,000 acres all the way out to 2978, which was a major acquisition.
But George became convinced.
If we didn't do that, by the way, we'd be nearing the end of this project by now.
Because we needed that to grow.
So you come back here then in 74.
And that was kind of a tenuous time.
Yeah, oil shortages were coming on and the economy was flat and it was tough getting going.
By energy going up, they could afford to bridge the gap of deficit years until the project would turn profitable.
What intrigued you about coming here, say, instead of going to another project somewhere else?
Well, I think it was, frankly, the biggest project.
I really believed that it had all the components for success, as I mentioned, on a state highway near a growing metropolitan area.
the largest in the country at that time, near a major airport.
So those compounds were there.
George's personal commitment to me that this was not a get in and get out kind of a project.
He was going to see it through.
They were going to fund it.
And the thing that appealed to me most of all the sponsors of New Towns, most of them were either in the real estate business or some other affiliated business, but nobody had such a strong
main business.
I think Mitchell's energy division, and we used to say, you know, Mitchell is 80% energy and 20% real estate.
So real estate's very cyclonic.
If you're going into a project that's going to take 30 years, there's going to be good times, there's going to be bad times, there's going to be good times, there's going to be bad times.
It's going to go up and down two or three times a decade.
And if that's all you do, when you hit those troughs, you're in a lot of trouble.
I saw the energy division as the means to bridge those gaps, where when things are good, we break it all in.
When things get bad, we've got the staying power.
I never would have sold my company, you know, just to come out of purely real estate companies.
I know they're so flaky.
They don't have the staying power when you hit a recession.
But since it was a minor part of the company's business, you know,
I figured that gave it a stability that most real estate companies don't have.
It's a very important thing.
And people will admit, if you look back, that if it weren't for energy, we wouldn't have produced some of the gas.
And then, of course, we had the double whammy in the mid-'80s, when both energy and real estate went down, and we had some tough sledding.
But now, both of them up again.
I think it's going to work out all right.
I think that... Do you think, incidentally, that...
Right now, it's comparable in any way, say, to the mid-'70s when things began to recycle again.
You know, the energy oil went up and building...
I like to think that we've learned something from that and we aren't going to go...
I think they'll find a solution in the next 6 to 12 months in the Middle East.
It'll be a compromise that will moderate things back to, I think, where it will stay...
between $20 and $30 a barrel, and maybe $25, where I think it's a healthy thing for the energy companies, but not a depressant on the rest of the world economy.
And I think that's very important.
But I think that will happen.
And instead of having the kind of crazy boom they had in the late 70s that only could foresee a collapse that happened, hopefully that won't happen again.
Now, when NAD
See, I may be jumping your head too far.
But in 82, that's about the time you begin to hit the slide again in the Woodlands.
What are you doing now?
I mean, can you sort of reconstruct that particular period?
You've been in the Boone, and now what happens is basically through the 80s.
Well, we reduced staff.
Our planning department used to be 18.
It went back to six.
It was a time to tighten belts and to try to...
survive what everybody said, what you know.
Because we know, historically, it's cyclonic.
When things are bad, they don't stay bad.
They will change.
They'll either get worse or they'll get better.
And we knew it would get better.
And sure enough, it did.
And the thing that happened, which was very surprising but very enlightening, as the real estate market shrunk as far as demand goes in Houston, so did
The development industries shrink.
And the subdivision developers, the shelter builders, as I said, the people who didn't build communities, their projects died illegally.

And what happened where the Newtown-type projects, which the Woodlands fits the Newtown definition the best, but there are others that are similar but not quite as complete, like the King Woods and the First Colonies and the Copperfields, those planned communities, which

fortunately ring Clear Lake City, ring Houston, and that's an important point to mention later, those communities which had been getting between 5 and 7 percent of the market share during the good times wound up getting 50 to 55 percent of the market share.
So while the pie got smaller, the new community project share of that pie got bigger and bigger.
So we didn't suffer
the total collapse that the individual subdivision developers saw.
And that was largely because of the builders or whatever lost their financing, was it, do you think?
That's probably part of it, but also I think that the marketplace began to understand and perceive that a new community environment
Was it better protection for their real estate investment than somebody's bedroom in the subdivision?

Right, somebody's gridiron bedroom community project that didn't have the recreation, social, cultural, entertainment, and employment opportunities where the quality of life wasn't assured because of the completeness of the program and the plan.
And then that was traditional Texas, Houston construction style until the advent of equipment.
across the whole country.
And I'm not trying to compare anything unfavorably, but Friendswood, I guess, would have been the largest developer in the south part of town in that style.
Clear Lake City.
Clear Lake City, right.
Are they moving more into your style of development now, you think?
No, I don't think so.
I think everyone has their own program.
Our biggest competitor, because the two of us are the north side of town, their villages are economically very monolithic.
This village, if you want a price range house, $150,000 to $200,000, you live in that village.
If you want an $80,000 house, you live in another village.
Where the woodlands, we have the dynamics of a complete socioeconomic mixed formula for the whole village.
And we get more vitality and reality to the population that way.
And we put 12,000 to 16,000, 18,000 people per village to serve as a village center.
Kingwood just does residential pods, and they call them villages, but they're not.
We try to have a village center and school system, short of high school, in each village, complete parks and pathway systems for each village, complete variety of housing in each village.
So people are triggered to have a sense of allegiance and place in the village they live in.
And then we do a village in four to five, six years.
We're done with it, and we're on to another village, and these people aren't in the construction mess anymore.
And we can take 30 years, and we aren't pestering everybody with 30 years worth of construction activity around their ears, because we do a village at a time.
They overlap, of course.
So you survived the slump, basically, by, in part, contracting some of your activities.
But also, your share of the pie is getting larger.
And we're talking about 82, 83 more pie, and so forth.
What are you doing now in terms of planning?
Is there any kind of redirection or reconstitution of your thoughts and directions?
Well, only those that I think come from the maturing of the project.
And I think that...

you understand our master plan we have a 5 000 acre business complex along the i-45 corridor there hasn't been much said about it uh i don't think if you ask people downtown about the woodlands they would immediately talk about housing and that segment of it they think of it as a business community
Yet the Woodlands has 5,000 acre business complex, which makes it one of the largest master plan business complex in the southwestern part of the United States.
We have a rail served industrial park at the trade center.
We have a commercial area for light manufacturing.
We have the research forest for high tech.
We have the town center, which will be the urban core.
5,000 acres will someday have 100,000 jobs and 30, 40 million square feet of development there, and it will be the hub of a million people by the year 2000.
That million people is the primary market area of the town center and the business complex of the Woodlands.
How many of that million will be housed actually in the Woodlands, let's say?
Will that be the Woodlands?
That will all be in the Woodlands.
Okay.
Right.

and that is the maturing of this region and that's what we're getting into the planning of now which you really couldn't think seriously about until you built up this base of 30 to 50 000 people here now the rest of it starts to come along and i think by the year 2000 we will have a business complex the town center particularly will start to take shape that will be the envy of any urban center
It'll be a satellite city to Houston, and it will be a downtown in the forest.
We'll have the amenities of culture, and education, and services, and shopping, and jobs that are in close proximity to the primary labor force in the area.
And I hope that that will really complete the spectrum that I consider the Woodlands.
And I think, you know, you don't start off doing that.
That can only come after the population in the region starts to mature, and we're within a year or two of reaching those kind of numbers.
Now, the Mall is intrinsic to that.
The Mall is one of those major building blocks or cornerstones of the town center.
A mall will not be viable unless there's 275 or 325,000 people within the primary market area.
And the arithmetic is now there.
So we're on the verge of being able to start that mall and bring it on stream in the next probably 24 months.
In developing this kind of, I won't call it an urban complex, but certainly a highly large population in a small area,
What does this do to your environmental concerns in the woodlands?
How do you manage that?
Is there a special plan?
In other words, when you put the mall down in the woodlands, how do you accommodate that to the style that you've already developed?
Is there difficulty here?
Well, any large project, such as a mall, requires a lot of earth moving, which of itself destroys a lot of trees.

uh but you have to have parking lots that enter at the second level can be two of them all but we will have site planning and architectural control of the design and development of this such that we will re-establish the forest in the parking lots and around the perimeter of the mall so that it still reads like the woodlands and not like uh some of your other yeah that's what that's the only
You know, 90 acres of concrete parking lots, period.
But you've certainly done that with the commercial buildings, even like your building.
You have to really walk through the trees to find the building.
It's kind of fun.
Man is a creature of the forest, which, you know, it's another dimension which I think is worth mentioning.
When I started work at Columbia, Maryland, and then these other new towns started following, there was a point in time when
I think if you added up our client list, we had over 100,000 acres worth of new community projects, which potentially could house a million people.
And I said, you know, this is serious work.
If you have the audacity to think you're going to build an environment for a million people, you really need to know something about people.
So up until that point, most of the concern was economics, market share.
sewer capacity, water capacity, highway access, the hardware issues.
Nobody was asking questions about, what about the user?
And I got involved at that point in personal research into cultural anthropology and social behavioral science in order to understand better what communities were all about.
I took eight trips to Europe and studied
various countries, their human settlements, their villages, their towns.

I wrote to Robert Ardrey's publisher in London and got invited to go to Rome where he was living and review with him for a week what someone who was a master at human behavior and social contract and the territorial imperative of people, what that could mean to the planning of new communities.
And as a result of that time, we became very good friends.

And I spent a lot of time in organizations and with authors who were mostly in academic situations studying about people and trying to quantify what it is they needed to lead successful lives and how that could impact the physical environment.
And for example, we found that in order to satisfy people, they come with one
pre-wired genetic propensities, which are just evolutionary in their character.
And second is the cultural imprinting of the environment they grew up in and the personal circumstances.
And that part, we didn't have much control about where people were coming from or whether their parents were good or bad.
There was enough psychiatrists out there and counselors to work on that.
But certainly, we could understand more about the basic needs of people.
And I came up with some simplistic ways of defining that for management by SIS.
First S stood for security.
All people yearn for security.
People that didn't worry about security aren't here anymore.
So that became an overriding tendency of people.
And you find it in the gated communities.
You find it in just the entrance statements, which are made to look like a gate.
That says, when I get in there, I'm safe.
That's a subtle appeal to man's innate need for security.
So we've organized the planning in the woodland so about 75% of all the single-family homes are on cul-de-sac courts.
A single point of entry, a defensible space.
The arithmetic of that group is such that it reinforces friendliness
and a sense of security that they're not with strangers.
There are friends and acquaintances there.
They're devoid of through traffic, so it's safer for the kids.
That's a whole sense of identity there, which is also the second point, which is personal identity.
People can be in big cities and they're lost because they don't have any contact with their neighbors.
You hear about it in New York.
People live in an apartment.
In 20 years, they never said hello to their neighbor in the next apartment.
We wanted to create a situation where people would feel free to intermingle and interact.
And the arithmetic of the group became very important.
So that's why I recreated that in the cul-de-sac developments in New Orleans.
That number, not coincidentally, is the same number that the average hunting primate troop.
Is that right?
It existed for two million years and tramped around this planet.
That's the same arithmetic.
Out of that kind of a group, you come up with five to ten able-bodied men, and the rest are children and women and older people and whatever.

And that five to ten able-bodied men happens to be the size of a baseball team and a football team and a basketball team, where instead of going out on the hunt with these able-bodied men, they've now got to organize team sports.
to replace that stimulation, which is an exciting question.
Stimulation.
That's great.
You can't have a bedroom community that's dull and monotonous if you're going to build a new community.
So we built in festivals.
No matter where I went and studied human civilization, back to the early towns in Mesopotamia 10,000 years ago, they all had amphitheaters.
They all had theater and music.
And we've worked hard.
And that's why for the last 10 years I worked hard to convince George that we needed this music pavilion.
And finally got funded to get the darn thing built.
And I was the project director on that that just opened last April, which was such a sense of accomplishment for me after 10 years of working hard on that.
And it builds a niche.
People need stimulation.
As I mentioned, the creatures of the forest and these studies
The Woodlands is probably the only place that I know of in the United States where you can consistently travel through the forest on pathways that we've built, the hiking bike trail system.
Presently, over 54 miles of hiking bike trails in the Woodlands.
It's recreating an old trick.
People love it.
Post-occupancy interviewing says, what do you like most about the Woodlands?
The statement comes up first, the pathways.
The walk.
They don't know.
I'm telling you, it recreates a pathway through the forest trip on foot or on bicycle or jogging.
Something in the midbrain is saying, gee, this is the way it always was.
This is great.
This is relaxing.
This is natural.
And if you're not in a forest, you bring it into your office or you bring the secretaries the plants on their desk.
I mean, there's an affinity between man and nature that can't be denied.
The Fares doesn't make people feel insecure or unsafe.
Well, it's the way it's always been.
This company, for example, if you're president, you get three trees in your office.
If you're senior vice president, you're entitled to two.
If you're state president, you get one.
If you're secretary, you bring your own pots and plants home and put it on your desk.
But that and flowers, I mean, the evidence is all around us.
You open it up and look, and then you try and reinforce that.
Festivals was the other thing.
We have festivals here, the Harvest Festival, the Fourth of July Festival, and sports festival events, like the Houston Open and swimming meets.
There's always something for people to be anticipating.
Sometimes the anticipation is more fun than the actual event, but you're adding some spice to life to say, boy, I can't wait until next Saturday night.
So-and-so is going to be at the pavilion, or we're going to have a golf tournament, or we're going to have a tennis tournament, or something else is happening.
And that, I think, is what the marketplace is beginning to respond to.
We're not just building shelter.
We've surrounded people with a quality of life here that they can't find anywhere else in Houston or probably in the country.
In the few short years we've been here, we've started to fill in the niches of what is a maximum opportunity for quality of life?
What is quality of life?
It's more than just shelter, having a nice bathroom, having a nice tile and countertops in your kitchen.
It's what is the environment in the community.

And most real estate developers, if I start talking to them about cultural anthropology or social behavioral science, we'll find another project where that's a positive ingredient to the planning process.
I would think so, too.
That's a good statement.
Yeah, that's brilliant.
And that picture on the wall over there is Robert Ardrey and I in old Rome.
He wrote the African Genesis, the Social Contract, the Territorial Imperative, and the Hunting Hypothesis.
A giant in his field.
He came before sociobiology by Wilson.
And yet all of those following quote, he was the leader in that field.
He's helped me change my mind about how to plan communities for people.
And the woodlands is the living example of those theories.
which need to be defined and stated and published.
That's a good statement.
And so the SIS, again, to summarize.
Security, identity, stimulation.
And if you have those three, you have the last one, which I added.
SIS came from my debates with Audrey.
That's love.
And that's love of self, family, neighbors, and your community.
It's allegiance.
It's what people die for.
Allegiance to a place.
When the city of Houston wants to annex the woodlands, there's going to be a tremendous outcry because the people have sunk their roots in here.
They have an allegiance to this place.
The territorial imperative of human beings is you defend your turf.
If you didn't defend your turf, you did not survive because the food scale, food stock was such that the human primate troops
Get up in the morning, go out, hunt, food gather, come back to a certain area.
That could support your 40 to 50 people.
If you let people come and nibble off your side, there wasn't enough food, you died.
So you defended territory.
People put up fences.
They argue about a foot of property.
It doesn't matter.
When I used to serve, I said, why are you worried about this?
It's my property.
Later, I learned there's a sense of territory.
You didn't defend it, it meant
death.
And the people that didn't defend turf to the death didn't reproduce to be here.
So it's been reinforced, reinforced, all down through the millennium.
And now we're territorially defensive people.
We want to defend our territory.
We were in trouble in the Middle East.
Those people were defended.
Sure.
We were in trouble in Vietnam.
You cannot send an army to a foreign place and have them fight anywhere near
the ferocity of somebody if you're on their land.
It's like a puppy dog in your yard.
You see what happens in a football game at the goal line.
When the defenders get their backs to the goal line, it's amazing how stronger their defense is.
It's a living proof that defense of territory, the closer you get to your property, the closer you, the harder you fight to defend it.
And the same thing is here.
There's an allegiance to this place, and I'm telling you, I've known more people in 15 years, 16 years, because their company sent them away.
They left any number of them, quit their job for 15 years seniority because they wanted to come back here with them.
My secretary's husband transferred to San Francisco, 17 years with the company, big promotion.
He said, I'm not going.
I said, you're crazy.
He said, I'm not going.
You can't throw that away.
I'm not going.
He went to school and studied real estate, started a whole new career after 17 because he wouldn't leave here.
I mean, it's an amazing example.
If you say to me the theories that I have on S-I-S plus love, L, they're working.
And when I go out and talk to people in the community and I
listen to what they say back.
I don't know if you have.
You need to do this in the classroom.
That's a capacity.
Well, I do.
You do?
Good.
I'm an adjunct professor up at A&M.
Good.
OK. Where are you from?
A&M.
Yeah.
I teach in the history department.
So I do this to the College of Architecture once a year to the graduate division.
And I also do the same thing at the University of Houston School of Architecture.

is talk about community planning and i try to get them beyond the facade and the hardware and the design of things right say what you're really you're trying to build environments for people if you build a great environment for people that they aspire to be in to be part of that will breed success and you'll be rewarded by the money that you make too many developers too you know you add up all the numbers dollars in dollars out and there's a profit
So they're fighting to make these numbers work.
And I just say, OK, the accountants can do that.
I'm going to build an environment that's so good that people will come.
They'll pay anything to buy a house there, even if it's more than somewhere else.
And then I'll get rewarded because I did a good job creating that environment.
